      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The procedural approach is often seen as a rigid, rule-bound method that prioritizes consistency over protecting evolving human rights, while the substantive approach is the necessary engine of a living Constitution that allows the law to adapt to new moral realities. You cannot rely solely on procedural rules to protect fundamental liberties like reproductive choice or marriage equality when the text itself is silent, making substantive due process an inevitable and vital tool for justice. Ultimately, a legal system that ignores substantive due process risks becoming a static document that fails to protect the very freedoms it was designed to safeguard.",
      "source": "target",
